'''Far-red''' light is light at the extreme [[red]] end of the [[visible spectrum]], just before [[infra-red]] light. Usually regarded as the region between 710 and 850&nbsp;nm [[wavelength]], it is dimly visible to some organisms' eyes. It is largely reflected or transmitted by [[plants]] because of the [[absorbance]] spectrum of [[chlorophyll]], and it is perceived by the plant [[photoreceptor protein|photoreceptor]] [[phytochrome]]. However, some organisms can use it as a source of energy in photosynthesis.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.bbabio.2005.05.005| title = Photosynthetic activity of far-red light in green plants| journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Bioenergetics| volume = 1708| issue = 3| pages = 311| year = 2005| last1 = Pettai| first1 = Hugo| last2 = Oja| first2 = Vello| last3 = Freiberg| first3 = Arvi| last4 = Laisk| first4 = Agu}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1399-3054.1969.tb07406.x| title = Adaptations in Pigment Composition and Photosynthesis by Far Red Radiation in Chlorella pyrenoidosa| journal = Physiologia Plantarum| volume = 22| issue = 3| pages = 516| year = 1969| last1 = Oquist| first1 = Gunnar}}</ref> Far-red light also is used for vision by certain organisms such as some species of deep-sea fishes.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Dragon fish see using chlorophyll | doi = 10.1038/30871| year = 1998| last1 = Douglas| first1 = R. H.| journal = Nature| volume = 393| issue = 6684| pages = 423| last2 = Partridge| first2 = J. C.| last3 = Dulai| first3 = K.| last4 = Hunt| first4 = D.| last5 = Mullineaux| first5 = C. W.| last6 = Tauber| first6 = A. Y.| last7 = Hynninen| first7 = P. H.| bibcode = 1998Natur.393..423D}}</ref><ref>{{cite new | title = Scientists Discover Unique Microbe In California's Largest Lake | publisher = [[ScienceDaily]] | date = 11 January 2005 | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2005/01/050110112808.htm}}</ref>

